# Requirements — <scope name>

Brief one-paragraph statement of what this scope is responsible for and how it fits in the larger system. Cite the upstream input (parent requirements, product brief, user stories) by ID.

## Glossary

```yaml
glossary:
  - term: "<canonical term>"
    definition: |
      <single, complete-sentence definition>
    distinct_from: <optional — similar concepts and how they differ>
    model_refs: <optional — entity / value-object / aggregate names>

  # Add one entry per domain term used anywhere in this document.
```

## Inherited Constraints

```yaml
inherited_constraints:
  - id: IC-<scope>-<NNN>
    source: "<citation: ADR / regulation / contract / policy>"
    summary: |
      <what the constraint requires, in one or two sentences>
    category: <technical | regulatory | organisational | financial | temporal>
    cost_of_relaxing: |
      <what specifically would break if this were lifted>
    derived_requirements: [<list of REQ-IDs>]
```

## Functional Requirements

```yaml
- id: REQ-<scope>-<NNN>
  type: functional
  statement: |
    <EARS-shaped statement: ubiquitous, event-driven, state-driven,
     optional-feature, or unwanted-behaviour>
  acceptance: |
    # optional — use when the statement alone leaves test conditions ambiguous
    Given <state>
    When <trigger>
    Then <observable response>
  rationale: |
    <why this requirement; the option chosen and the alternatives considered>
  derived_from: [<upstream IDs>]
  derivation: <derived-only — omit for normal requirements>
```

## Quality Attributes (NFRs)

```yaml
- id: REQ-<scope>-<NNN>
  type: quality_attribute
  statement: |
    The <SYSTEM/SUBSYSTEM, named>
    shall <RESPONSE>
    in <METRIC + UNIT>
    at <TARGET at correct statistical level — e.g. p95>
    under <CONDITION — load + environment + measurement point>.
  # OR multi-level form:
  planguage:
    scale: "<what is measured>"
    meter: "<how, over what window>"
    fail:    "<below which the system is in violation>"
    goal:    "<committed target>"
    stretch: "<desirable, not committed>"
    wish:    "<aspirational>"
  rationale: |
    <derivation of the target; what trade-off; cite parent-scope NFR if applicable>
  derived_from: [<upstream IDs>]
```

## Interface Requirements

```yaml
- id: REQ-<scope>-<NNN>
  type: interface
  operation: "<name and method>"
  protocol: |
    <wire protocol + version + transport security; cite RFC/spec where applicable>
  message_structure:
    request: [...]
    response_2xx: [...]
    response_4xx: [...]
    response_5xx: [...]
  timing: |
    <latency target; rate limits; retry expectations; timeouts>
  error_handling: |
    <what happens on each failure mode; retry policy; failure threshold>
  startup_initial_state: |
    <cold-start behaviour; readiness signal; first-request-after-restart>
  precondition: [<caller guarantees>]
  postcondition_on_success: [<system guarantees on success>]
  postcondition_on_error: [<system guarantees on each error response>]
  invariants: [<conditions true before and after, always>]
  versioning: |
    <version label; compatibility regime; deprecation policy>
  rationale: |
    <why this contract; security/auditability/idempotency reasoning as applicable>
  derived_from: [<upstream IDs>]
```

## Data Requirements

```yaml
- id: REQ-<scope>-<NNN>
  type: data
  statement: |
    <statement about format, retention, privacy class, integrity invariants>
  rationale: |
    <why this data rule; cite regulatory or architectural source if applicable>
  derived_from: [<upstream IDs>]
```

## Notes

- Replace `<placeholders>` with concrete content.
- Every requirement needs `rationale`; if none is recoverable, mark `pending` (greenfield) or `unknown` (retrofit) — **never fabricate**.
- Run `references/quality-bar-checklist.md` before delivering.
- Run `references/anti-patterns.md` sweep before delivering.
